
# Abstract


   This article will use the relational inequality (RIT) theory in combination with graph theory, to understand how social relationships at the worksite can explain economic inequality. 
   RIT is a framework for understanding the dynamics of economic inequality at an organizational level, focusing on worksites as the unit of analysis, and the variance between worksites as a scientific interest in itself. The focus is on the relative status composition of categorically distinct groups within a workplace, and how these play out to produce outcomes differentiated by group status and the intersection of group identities, the effectiveness of which is primarily determined at the worksite level. 
   While RIT has a strong and empirically validated claim for the case of intraorganizational group composition as an important part of inequality, the dynamics of these groups conceptualized in network terms and with network metrics has not been part of the research agenda. It is argued here that network dynamics is a crucial part of organizational life, and that it helps us understand the relations of power between groups. Using administrative data from Denmark, network metrics on a per-worksite basis is used to explain outcomes. 








